<h2>Arkansas Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Arkansas offers several valuable incentives for solar and energy efficiency improvements, with the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) serving as the primary financial incentive for solar installations. This credit allows homeowners to deduct 30% of the total cost of their solar system from their federal taxes, including equipment, installation, and related expenses. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this represents \$6,000 in tax savings. The 30% credit is available through 2032, after which it steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034 before expiring for residential installations.</p>

<p>At the state level, Arkansas provides a valuable property tax exemption for solar energy systems. This exemption means that the added value of a solar installation will not increase property tax assessments, providing ongoing savings throughout the system's lifetime. For a solar system that adds \$15,000-25,000 in home value, this exemption can save homeowners \$150-400 annually in property taxes, depending on local tax rates.</p>

<p>Entergy Arkansas, the state's primary utility provider, offers various energy efficiency rebates and programs that can be combined with solar installations. These include rebates for high-efficiency HVAC systems, smart thermostats, and whole-home energy efficiency improvements. The utility's residential energy efficiency programs can provide rebates of \$300-800 for qualifying HVAC upgrades, and additional incentives for comprehensive home energy improvements when combined with solar installations.</p>

<p>Local utilities and municipalities throughout Arkansas may offer additional rebates and incentives. Many electric cooperatives provide rebates for heat pump installations and energy efficiency upgrades. Cities like Fayetteville and Little Rock have periodically offered additional incentives for renewable energy installations, and homeowners should check with their local utility and municipal government for current programs.</p>

